Vheadline
p2
VA musical feast
p3
sVnews
p4
VVisakha Music Academy featured a vocal recital by Maharajapuram S. Ramachandran of Chennai last Saturday at Kalabharathi. Ramachandran is the seventh in the direct sishya parampara of Thyagaraja and was trained under his paternal grandfather Viswanadha Iyer first and then his father Santhanam.He was invited to perform\u000asolo for Akashvani, Madras\u000aMusic Academy, and so on in\u000a1978. Emerging as a name to\u000areckon with, he won many\u000aawards from well-established\u000aSangeetha Sabhas and was\u000aconferred with titles like Sangeetha\u000aChoodamani, Arsha\u000aKalabhooshanam, and Tamil\u000aIsai Vendhar.In the company of Kumbakonam\u000aM.R. Gopinath on the\u000aviolin and R. Ramesh on mridangam,\u000a(both from Chennai),\u000aRamachandran made\u000abest use of his expressive\u000avoice that could go over two\u000aoctaves with the same intensity.\u000aHe got off to a spellbinding\u000astart with the Begada\u000avarnam. He concluded it with\u000ascintillating swaram, replete\u000awith scholarly sojourns on\u000athe specific madhyamam and\u000athe two nishadams placed in\u000apertinently coined phrases\u000asurfacing the Vakrashaadava\u000aSampoorna Rakthi Raga Bhavam\u000aaesthetically in its entirety.After singing the nata keerthana\u000aSivatraya Mahaganapathim\u000awith swaram again on\u000asimilar lines, he enthrallingly\u000arendered Saaramegani (Pantuvarali)\u000aof Thyagaraja with\u000aaalapana, neravu and swaram.\u000aThis was followed by\u000a(Aarabhi) of Swathi Tirunal\u000asuffixed with swaram in the\u000atwo tempos, a composition\u000aSaranga in Ragamalika, and\u000aMadhava Kesava (Shanmukhapriya)\u000aprefixed with aalapana.\u000aThen he expansively\u000aexpatiated Manasu Swaadheenamaina\u000a(Sankarabharanam)\u000awith empathetic\u000aintonation.The tail-piece was mostly\u000amade up of listener's requests\u000alike Sree Chakra Raja Simhasane\u000a(Ragamalika), Bhuvaneswariya\u000a(Mohana), and\u000aSivaranjani Tillana.
